   ### ROOT CAUSE
   program.cpp:3-5: The `fib` function is defined recursively without base cases
   to terminate the recursion (e.g., for `n <= 1`). This causes infinite
   recursive calls with decreasing `n` values that eventually become negative,
   allocating stack frames without bound until the stack overflows, resulting in
   a segmentation fault when the program attempts to access memory beyond the
   stack limit.
   
   ### LOCAL FIX
   Add minimal base cases to terminate recursion for small non-negative `n`.
   This prevents infinite recursion and stack overflow, though the exponential
   time complexity remains (the program will run very slowly for `n=100` but
   won't crash).
   
   Replacement code for lines 3-5:
   ```
   int fib(int n) {
     if (n == 0) return 0;
     if (n == 1) return 1;
     return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
   }
   ```
   (For negative `n`, this still recurses infinitely, but since the input is
   100, it won't be hit. A more robust local fix could add `if (n < 0) return
   0;` or throw an error, but that's not minimal.)
   
   ### GLOBAL FIX
   Redesign `fib` to use an iterative approach instead of recursion, eliminating
   the risk of stack overflows from deep recursion entirely. This prevents this
   class of bugs (unbounded or excessive recursion depth) by avoiding recursion,
   while also improving performance to O(n) time and O(1) space. For example:
   
   Replacement code for lines 3-5:
   ```
   int fib(int n) {
     if (n <= 0) return 0;
     if (n == 1) return 1;
     int a = 0, b = 1;
     for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {
       int temp = a + b;
       a = b;
       b = temp;
     }
     return b;
   }
   ```
   This structural change (iteration over recursion) ensures scalability for
   large `n` without relying on the call stack.
